pelvic floor

The pelvic floor or pelvic diaphragm is the name given to the group of muscles which make up the base of the pelvic cavity and support the abdominal viscera. These muscles stretch from the pubis to the coccyx and form a sling around the rectum and genitals and work to tighten or relax the urogenital and rectal hiatuses. The broad name for this stretch of these muscles is the levator ani given its function in tightening and elevating the anal opening but is made up of a group of muscles.
